          <text>
            Different from Leafwhisper and Rootwalker's information-versus-silence, and different from Streamwalker and Brightbloom's calm-versus-energy—every guide pair has their own language. And I'm learning to speak all of them.

            The slope levels off into a plateau and I stop to catch my breath, turning to look back the way we came. The wetlands are visible in the distance—flat and glittering with water, completely different terrain. We've climbed higher than I realized.

            Oakshade says, "The view expands with elevation—distance provides perspective."

            I say, "It's beautiful." And it is—purple sky reflecting in the wetland pools, the darker line of the forest beyond that. Three territories, three completely different worlds.

            Mossmantle says, "Another three hours to tonight's rest area—two more climbs, both steeper—water source at the campsite."

            Right—beautiful views are nice, but we still have to keep walking. I take a long drink from my water supply, Scout bounces back from their exploration, and we continue.

            The afternoon is all hills: up one slope, down the other side, up the next. My legs burn—not the sharp pain of injury but the deep ache of muscles working hard. It's different from forest walking or wetland slogging; everything engages—calves for pushing uphill, thighs for controlling downhill, core for balance on uneven ground.

            Buddy—quiet, supportive—says, "Kira—your heart rate is elevated! This is excellent cardiovascular exercise. Did you know that hill climbing engages sixty percent more muscle groups than level terrain walking—"

            I say, "I can feel that, Buddy. Physically feeling it right now."

            Buddy says, "Oh—of course—apologies. You're doing very well."

            I blink— that was just supportive, not a teaching moment—just genuine encouragement.

            I say, "Thanks, Buddy."

            Buddy is learning too.

            Scout finds something interesting—a cluster of crystalline rocks that catch the light. They bounce excitedly, rolling around the formation—clearly wanting me to see it.

            I say, "Very pretty, Scout."

            Mossmantle says, "Those form from mineral deposits—water seeps through, leaves minerals behind—takes many cycles."

            Oakshade says, "Patience crystallized—slow processes creating lasting beauty."

            See—that's actually kind of lovely. Oakshade's philosophy works better when it's about rocks than about climbing.

            We reach the evening campsite as the sun is setting. It's a sheltered spot between two rock formations—wind protection on three sides, flat ground for sleeping, and a small spring trickling down the rocks. Territory maintenance has been here—the ground is cleared, there's a fire pit—plants apparently like fires for light even though they don't need heat—and soft moss has been encouraged to grow in sleeping-sized patches.

            I drop my pack with a groan of relief—my shoulders appreciate the break.
          </text>
